2F%2Fwww.thebetterindia.com%2F342929%2Fias-sonal-goel-upsc-cse-mains-preparation-strategy-for-general-studies-topper-tips%2F%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Becoming%20Human%3A%20Shaped%20by%20Ice%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22192550%2FMorteratsch_glacier_1-1.jpeg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20is%20the%20fourth%20article%20in%20a%20series%20about%20the%20Earth-system%20%E2%80%93%20how%20our%20planet%20has%20shaped%20us%20as%20human%20beings%2C%20and%20how%20we%2C%20in%20turn%2C%20have%20shaped%20it.%20Read%20the%20series%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fearths-changing-climate%5C%22%3EPart%201%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0%7C%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fa-planetary-perspective%5C%22%3EPart%202%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%20%7C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fbecoming-human-forged-by-fire%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EPart%203%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOur%20planet%20has%20experienced%20great%20temperature%20fluctuations%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fa-planetary-perspective%5C%22%3Ethroughout%20its%20past%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Even%20in%20the%20Pleistocene%20ice%20age%2C%20beginning%20about%202.5%20million%20years%20ago%20and%20continuing%20until%20the%20present%2C%20average%20global%20temperatures%20have%20repeatedly%20cycled%20between%20extremes%20of%20five%20or%20six%20degrees.%20When%20the%20temperatures%20swung%20downward%2C%20glaciers%20engulfed%20large%20parts%20of%20Eurasia%2C%20North%20America%2C%20and%20Greenland%2C%20burying%20the%20midlatitudes%2C%20which%20we%20consider%20temperate%20today%2C%20under%20mountains%20of%20ice.%20We%20call%20those%20frigid%20periods%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncei.noaa.gov%2Fsites%2Fdefault%2Ffiles%2F2021-11%2F1%252520Glacial-Interglacial%252520Cycles-Final-OCT%2525202021.pdf%5C%22%3Eglaciations%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20air%20was%20cold%20and%20dry%3B%20subtropical%20deserts%20expanded%20or%20shifted%20their%20locale.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20321px)%2085vw%2C%20321px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22321%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%20874w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-219x300.jpg%20219w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-746x1024.jpg%20746w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-696598%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22440%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIllustration%3A%20Pariplab%20Chakraborty%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20when%20the%20temperatures%20cycled%20upward%20again%2C%20the%20glacial%20periods%20were%20broken%20by%20spells%20of%20great%20warmth%2C%20called%20%3Cem%3Einterglacials%3C%2Fem%3E.%20The%20air%20grew%20warmer%20and%20moister%3B%20deserts%20like%20the%20Sahara%20might%20even%20bloom%20with%20grasses.%20Forests%20expanded%2C%20and%20animals%20moved%20to%20higher%20latitudes%20across%20the%20continents%20or%20into%20higher%20elevations%20on%20the%20mountainsides.%20%3Cem%3EInterglacial%3C%2Fem%3E%20temperatures%20were%20more%20like%20what%20we%20consider%20historically%20%E2%80%98normal.%E2%80%99%20Yet%20the%20glaciers%20always%20came%20lurching%20back%2C%20devouring%20mountains%20and%20plains%20and%20rivers%20with%20their%20tongues%20of%20ice%2C%20continually%20remaking%20the%20landscape.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20fact%2C%20for%20the%20past%20million%20years%2C%20glacial%20conditions%20have%20dominated%20the%20planet%20with%20each%20episode%20typically%20lasting%20around%2090%2C000%20years%2C%20while%20the%20interglacials%20each%20lasted%20less%20than%2015%2C000%20years.%20And%20all%20of%20recorded%20human%20history%20has%20occurred%20only%20during%20our%20present%20interglacial%20episode%2C%20called%20the%20Holocene%2C%20which%20began%2011%2C700%20years%20ago%2C%20continuing%20until%20modern%20times.%20If%20humans%20had%20not%20so%20radically%20changed%20the%20climate%2C%20our%20present%20interglacial%20would%20also%20have%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41598-018-28419-5.pdf%5C%22%3Ecome%20to%20an%20end%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20temperatures%20sliding%20back%20toward%20the%20next%20glacial%20phase%2C%20in%20keeping%20with%20the%20longstanding%20patterns%20of%20the%20Pleistocene.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20cycling%20of%20the%20climate%20through%20cooler-dryer%20and%20warmer-wetter%20millennia%2C%20the%20expanding%20and%20shrinking%20of%20glaciers%2C%20rising%20and%20falling%20of%20sea%20levels%2C%20was%20the%20world%20into%20which%20early%20humans%20evolved.%20Yet%20we%20shouldn%E2%80%99t%20presume%20our%20ancestors%20were%20miserable%20brutes%20mutely%20suffering%20these%20conditions%3B%20it%20makes%20no%20more%20sense%20to%20imagine%20they%20hated%20the%20ice%20age%20than%20to%20imagine%20that%20polar%20bears%20hate%20the%20Arctic%20today%20or%20that%20whales%20hate%20the%20sea.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20few%20remains%20of%20early%20hominins%20found%20in%20the%20Indian%20subcontinent%20include%20a%20partial%20skull%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.currentscience.ac.in%2FVolumes%2F103%2F12%2F1461.pdf%5C%22%3Epartial%20leg%20bones%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20so-called%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ffrontline.thehindu.com%2Fscience-and-technology%2Farticle30162596.ece%5C%22%3ENarmada%20human%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Dated%20between%20250%2C000%E2%80%93200%2C000%20years%20old%2C%20these%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scirp.org%2Fjournal%2Fpaperinformation%3Fpaperid%3D102546%5C%22%3Eunique%20fossils%20share%20traits%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20both%20%3Cem%3E%20erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%20and%20archaic%20subspecies%20of%20%3Cem%3EH.%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3E%20sapiens%3C%2Fem%3E%20(like%20Denisovans).%20Both%20the%20age%20of%20the%20bones%20and%20their%20morphology%20suggest%20Narmada%20human%20could%20be%20either%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.academia.edu%2F4331363%2FWas_Homo_heidelbergensis_in_South_Asia_A_test_using_the_Narmada_fossil_from_central_India%5C%22%3Eintermediate%20form%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20hominin%20or%20perhaps%20a%20hybrid%20species%2C%20resulting%20from%20interbreeding%20between%20these%20very%20distant%20cousin%20lineages.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20ice%20age%20shaped%20what%20we%20are.%20And%20in%20it%20we%20thrived.%20Undaunted%20by%20ceaseless%20cycles%20of%20glaciation%2C%20our%20ancestral%20populations%20were%20growing.%20They%20would%20have%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fscience.thewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fleaning-into-indigenous-knowledge-on-climate-change%2F%5C%22%3Erecorded%20features%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20landscape%20in%20their%20oral%20traditions%2C%20noting%20how%20things%20changed%20over%20generations%2C%20constructing%20legends%20and%20lessons%20from%20what%20they%20observed.%20With%20fire%20and%20stone%20tools%20in%20hand%2C%20groups%20of%20%3Cem%3EHomo%20Erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fhumanorigins.si.edu%2Fresearch%2Fasian-research-projects%2Fearliest-humans-china%5C%22%3Espread%20out%20of%20Africa%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20entering%20into%20Eurasian%20landscapes%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.smithsonianmag.com%2Fscience-nature%2Fwhat-drove-homo-erectus-out-of-africa-180978881%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DAccording%2525252520to%2525252520this%2525252520idea%2C%2525252520H%2Csavanna%2525252520into%2525252520the%2525252520Southern%2525252520Levant.%5C%22%3Enearly%20two%20million%20years%20ago%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20despite%20the%20icy%20cold.%20Their%20descendants%20separated%20over%20hundreds%20of%20millennia%20into%20several%20distinct%20populations%20known%20today%20by%20such%20names%20as%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FDmanisi_hominins%5C%22%3EDmanisi%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FPeking_Man%5C%22%3EPeking%20Man%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FJava_Man%5C%22%3EJava%20Man%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20the%20diminutive%20%E2%80%98%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fhumanorigins.si.edu%2Fresearch%2Fasian-research-projects%2Fhobbits-flores-indonesia%5C%22%3EHobbits%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%99%20of%20today%E2%80%99s%20Flores%20Island.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%20those%20who%20remained%20back%20in%20Africa%20also%20continued%20to%20evolve%20into%20a%20distinct%20population.%20By%20700%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20they%E2%80%99d%20come%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fhumanorigins.si.edu%2Fevidence%2Fhuman-fossils%2Fspecies%2Fhomo-heidelbergensis%5C%22%3Elook%20and%20behave%3C%2Fa%3E%20very%20much%20like%20us%20today.%20As%20their%20numbers%20grew%2C%20groups%20of%20them%20also%20began%20expanding%20out%20of%20Africa%2C%20burying%20their%20dead%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fscience.thewire.in%2Fthe-sciences%2Fneanderthals-more-knowable-now-than-ever%2F%5C%22%3Emaking%20clothes%20and%20jewellery%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20occasionally%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fscience%2F2016%2Fmay%2F25%2Fneanderthals-built-mysterious-cave-structures-175000-years-ago%5C%22%3Ebuilding%20walls%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Stockily%20built%20for%20the%20cold%2C%20much%20larger%20and%20stronger%20than%20we%20are%20today%2C%20they%20eventually%20replaced%20their%20distant%20cousins%20who%E2%80%99d%20gone%20before.%20Their%20descendant%20populations%20are%20sometimes%20called%20%3Cem%3Earchaic%20humans%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20including%20such%20types%20as%20Neanderthals%2C%20Denisovans%2C%20and%20others%20yet%20unnamed%2C%20some%20of%20whom%20lived%20until%20at%20least%2040%2C000%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20444px)%2085vw%2C%20444px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22192804%2FNeanderthaler_Krijn_800p.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22444%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22192804%2FNeanderthaler_Krijn_800p.jpg%20800w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22192804%2FNeanderthaler_Krijn_800p-300x264.jpg%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-698405%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22391%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EReconstructed%20face%20of%20a%20Neanderthal%20man%20who%20lived%20between%2070%E2%80%9340%20thousand%20years%20ago%20in%20what%20is%20today%20the%20Netherlands.%20Photo%3A%20Servaas%20Neijens%2FRijksmuseum%20website%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20it%20was%20their%20cousins%E2%80%94a%20third%20group%E2%80%94still%20remaining%20in%20Africa%2C%20who%20came%20to%20fully%20resemble%20us%2C%20%3Cem%3Eanatomically%20modern%20humans%2C%3C%2Fem%3E%20by%20around%20300%2C000%20years%20ago.%20These%20%3Cem%3Emodern%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Cem%3Ehumans%3C%2Fem%3E%20became%20the%20primary%20direct%20ancestors%20of%20all%20people%20living%20on%20earth%20today.%20Some%20of%20them%20also%20spread%20into%20Eurasia%2C%20first%20crossing%20into%20the%20Arabian%20Peninsula%20as%20early%20as%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC4844272%2F%5C%22%3E120%2C000%20years%20ago%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMigrating%20%3Cem%3Emodern%20humans%3C%2Fem%3E%20remained%20close%20to%20Africa%20for%20a%20very%20long%20time%2C%20eschewing%20the%20colder%20reaches%20of%20Eurasia.%20But%20some%20groups%20eventually%20followed%20the%20Asian%20coastline%20southward%20into%20the%20warmer%20Indian%20subcontinent%2C%20their%20descendants%20continuing%20eastward%20for%20a%20thousand%20generations%2C%20eventually%20reaching%20Australia%20before%2065%2C000%20years%20ago.%20All%20along%20the%20way%2C%20some%20of%20them%20stayed%20behind%2C%20separating%20into%20different%20cultural%20groups%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fneanderthals-died-out-40-000-years-ago-but-there-has-never-been-more-of-their-dna-on-earth-189021%5C%22%3Ere-mixing%20with%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Cem%3Earchaic%20humans%3C%2Fem%3E%20wherever%20they%20met.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETheir%20mixed%20descendants%20ventured%20further%20still%20and%2C%20somewhere%20in%20Eurasia%2C%20embarked%20upon%20a%20complex%20relationship%20with%20wolves%2C%20domesticating%20some%20of%20them%20as%20dogs.%20Some%20of%20these%20peoples%20crossed%20vast%20territories%20of%20permafrost%2C%20spreading%20themselves%E2%80%94now%20with%20companion%20dogs%20by%20their%20side%E2%80%94across%20much%20of%20icebound%2C%20northern%20Eurasia.%20They%20crossed%20Beringia%20into%20the%20Americas%20well%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.smithsonianmag.com%2Fscience-nature%2Foldest-fossil-human-footprints-in-north-america-are-23000-years-old-study-reaffirms-180983018%2F%5C%22%3Ebefore%2020%2C000%3C%2Fa%3E%20years%20ago%2C%20during%20the%20coldest%20period%20of%20the%20last%20glaciation.%20Before%2015%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20humans%20had%20colonised%20all%20six%20habitable%20continents%2C%20bringing%20dogs%20into%20five%20of%20them%20(not%20yet%20to%20Australia%2C%20where%20dogs%20were%20introduced%20many%20thousands%20of%20years%20later).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAncient%20hominins%20who%20still%20used%20the%20tools%20of%20%3Cem%3E%20erectus%20%3C%2Fem%3Eappear%20to%20have%20remained%20in%20the%20Thar%20Desert%20region%20until%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.shh.mpg.de%2F2057399%2Facheulean-persistence%5C%22%3E177%2C000%20years%20ago%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20longer%20than%20anywhere%20else%20in%20the%20world.%20When%20%3Cem%3Earchaic%20humans%3C%2Fem%3E%E2%80%94an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fnindia.2017.12%5C%22%3Eas-yet%20unidentified%20branch%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94were%20migrating%20into%20the%20subcontinent%2C%20they%20would%20have%20met%20these%20distant%20cousins.%20Other%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41598-021-98897-7%5C%22%3Eancient%20tools%20found%20in%20the%20same%3C%2Fa%3E%20region%20suggest%20a%20complex%20relationship%20between%20peoples%20who%20used%20extremely%20ancient%20and%20slightly%20more%20sophisticated%20tool%20technologies%2C%20giving%20further%20weight%20to%20the%20idea%20that%20very%20different%20human%20lineages%20were%20mixing%20and%20mingling%20in%20the%20subcontinent.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELike%20any%20species%20colonising%20new%20territories%2C%20humans%20disrupted%20every%20new%20ecosystem%20they%20entered.%20Their%20arrival%20in%20extreme%20northern%20latitudes%20and%20later%20in%20the%20Americas%20helped%20precipitate%20the%20demise%20of%20several%20megafaunal%20species%2C%20such%20as%20mammoths%20and%20mastodons%2C%20giant%20sloths%20and%20dire%20wolves.%20Similarly%2C%20in%20Australia%20giant%20species%20of%20mammals%20and%20crocodilians%20died%20out%20over%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.australiangeographic.com.au%2Ftopics%2Fscience-environment%2F2017%2F01%2Faboriginal-australians-co-existed-with-the-megafauna-for-at-least-17000-years%2F%5C%22%3Emany%20millennia%2C%20following%20humans%E2%80%99%20arrival%3C%2Fa%3E%20into%20their%20habitats.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThough%20there%E2%80%99s%20no%20evidence%20that%20people%20directly%20annihilated%20the%20megafauna%20through%20over-hunting%2C%20human%20presence%20certainly%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41467-021-21201-8%23%3A~%3Atext%3DThe%2525252520disappearance%2525252520of%2525252520many%2525252520North%2Csome%2525252520combination%2525252520of%2525252520the%2525252520two%5C%22%3Eimpacted%20local%20ecosystems%3C%2Fa%3E%20at%20multiple%20levels%2C%20both%20directly%20and%20indirectly%20changing%20entire%20landscapes%20in%20ways%20no%20one%20could%20have%20foreseen.%20As%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41467-023-43426-5%5C%22%3Ehuman%20presence%20altered%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20flows%20of%20energy%20and%20materials%20through%20these%20ecosystems%2C%20some%20species%20declined%20while%20others%20expanded.%20For%20instance%2C%20it%E2%80%99s%20likely%20the%20saber-toothed%20tiger%20was%20out-competed%20by%20humans%2C%20the%20new%20apex%20predators%20of%20North%20America%2C%20triggering%20a%20domino-effect%20of%20ecosystem%20changes.%20This%20wave%20of%20extinctions%20of%20very%20large%20animals%2C%20which%20swept%20the%20world%20between%2050%2C000%E2%80%9310%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20is%20called%20the%20Late%20Quaternary%20extinction%20event.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20Africa%2C%20by%20contrast%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.yale.edu%2F2020%2F12%2F08%2Fwhy-do-elephants-and-tigers-still-roam-india-study-offers-clues%5C%22%3Ewhere%20humans%20had%20co-evolved%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20their%20ecosystem%20over%20many%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20there%20was%20no%20similarly%20extreme%20collapse%20of%20megafauna.%20Across%20tropical%20Asia%20too%2C%20the%20Late%20Quaternary%20extinction%20was%20far%20less%20extreme%20than%20in%20Northern%20Eurasia%2C%20Australia%2C%20or%20the%20Americas.%20This%20is%20likely%20because%20the%20multiple%20waves%20of%20hominins%20who%20dispersed%20from%20Africa%20had%20been%20living%20within%20southern%20Asian%20ecosystems%20continuously%20for%20nearly%20two%20million%20years.%20(Many%20of%20those%20animals%20that%20survived%20through%20the%20Late%20Quaternary%2C%20however%2C%20haven%E2%80%99t%20survived%E2%80%94or%20won%E2%80%99t%20survive%E2%80%94the%20more%20recent%20and%20ongoing%20wave%20of%20extinctions%20since%20the%20Industrial%20Revolution.)%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOne%20can%20only%20imagine%20that%20witnessing%20the%20disappearance%20of%20magnificent%20and%20powerful%20creatures%20was%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fof-bunyips-and-other-beasts-living-memories-of-long-extinct-creatures-in-art-and-stories-113031%5C%22%3Edeeply%20affecting%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94even%20traumatising%E2%80%94to%20the%20cultural%20communities%20that%20were%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Flink.springer.com%2Farticle%2F10.1007%2Fs10745-018-0004-0%5C%22%3Eattempting%20to%20integrate%20themselves%3C%2Fa%3E%20into%20the%20rhythms%20and%20dynamics%20of%20their%20newfound%20homes%2C%20who%20had%20long%20understood%20other%20creatures%20to%20be%20their%20kin.%20They%20might%20have%20seen%20such%20extinctions%20as%20a%20sign%20that%20the%20land%20was%20somehow%20endangered%2C%20that%20something%20was%20terribly%20wrong%3B%20they%20might%20well%20have%20blamed%20their%20own%20arrival%2C%20or%20their%20poor%20judgment%20and%20practice%2C%20for%20the%20disaster.%20It%E2%80%99s%20surely%20no%20coincidence%20that%20the%20indigenous%20cultures%20of%20both%20Australia%20and%20the%20Americas%2C%20having%20witnessed%20the%20extinctions%20of%20megafauna%20in%20their%20ancestral%20pasts%2C%20both%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.resilience.org%2Fstories%2F2023-10-09%2Fholding-the-fire-episode-2-anne-poelina%2F%5C%22%3Epreserve%20knowledge%20systems%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20so%20essentially%20and%20profoundly%20articulate%20what%20we%20industrialised%20peoples%20might%20simplify%20as%20valuing%20%E2%80%98sustainability%E2%80%99%20or%20%E2%80%98ecosystem%20stewardship.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENevertheless%2C%20by%2020%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20human%20beings%20were%20already%20emerging%20as%20a%20substantial%20planetary%20force%E2%80%94nothing%20like%20we%20would%20eventually%20grow%20to%20become%2C%20but%20already%20occupying%20nearly%20all%20major%20land%20masses%20and%20contributing%20more%20and%20more%20profoundly%20to%20the%20shaping%20of%20their%20myriad%20ecosystems.%20However%2C%20most%20successful%20human%20groups%20were%20still%20discovering%20and%20following%20principles%20that%20worked%20%3Cem%3Ewith%3C%2Fem%3E%20the%20cycles%20of%20their%20landscapes%2C%20broadly%20enriching%20them%20within%20limits%2C%20rather%20than%20carelessly%20destroying%20or%20attempting%20to%20distend%20them%20for%20their%20own%20narrow%20gains.%20They%20understood%20that%20destroying%20the%20ecosystems%20that%20nourished%20them%20would%20be%20suicidal.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20few%20fossils%20of%20archaic%20humans%E2%80%94including%20two%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.currentscience.ac.in%2FVolumes%2F73%2F12%2F1110.pdf%5C%22%3Eclavicles%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.currentscience.ac.in%2FVolumes%2F88%2F05%2F0704.pdf%5C%22%3Epartial%20rib%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20leg%20bones%E2%80%94have%20been%20found%20along%20the%20Narmada%20River%2C%20belonging%20to%20several%20different%20populations%20who%20lived%20between%2075%2C000%E2%80%93150%2C000%20years%20ago.%20All%20of%20them%20were%20gracile%20peoples%20of%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scirp.org%2Fjournal%2Fpaperinformation%3Fpaperid%3D102546%5C%22%3Eshort%20stature%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20comparable%20to%20the%20Onges%20and%20Jarawas%20of%20the%20Andaman%20Islands.%20This%20suggests%20the%20earliest%20modern%20human%20populations%20who%20traversed%20the%20subcontinent%2C%20beginning%20some%2080%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20whose%20distant%20descendants%20went%20on%20to%20populate%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcore.ac.uk%2Fdownload%2Fpdf%2F82168831.pdf%5C%22%3Ethe%20Andamans%20and%20Australia%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20were%20were%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scirp.org%2Fpdf%2Faa_2020082714340789.pdf%5C%22%3Esimilarly%20sized%20to%20the%20Onges%20and%20Jarawas%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAs%20%3Cem%3Emodern%20humans%3C%2Fem%3E%20thrived%20for%20nearly%20300%2C000%20years%20through%20the%20wild%20climate%20fluctuations%20of%20the%20Pleistocene%20ice%20age%2C%20their%20cultural%20institutions%20and%20social%20norms%20included%20attentiveness%20to%20the%20land%20as%20much%20as%20cooperation%2C%20exploration%2C%20and%20invention.%20These%20cultural%20traits%20enabled%20them%20to%20invade%20and%20ultimately%20adjust%20their%20livelihoods%20to%20a%20vast%20range%20of%20conditions%20and%20climes.%20Warm-bloodedness%2C%20mutual-aid%20systems%2C%20and%20mastery%20of%20fire%20were%20essential%20to%20their%20ice-age%20success.%20Thus%20they%20came%20to%20be%20at%20home%20in%20almost%20every%20type%20of%20ecosystem%20on%20six%20continents%20when%20the%20warm%20climate%20regime%20of%20the%20Holocene%20interglacial%20arrived%20less%20than%2012%2C000%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EDuring%20the%20Holocene%2C%20the%20global%20average%20temperature%20fluctuated%20by%20only%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs41597-020-0530-7%2Ffigures%2F3%5C%22%3Eabout%201%C2%BAC%20from%20its%20peak%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20about%20seven%20thousand%20years%20ago%2C%20to%20its%20nadir%2C%20between%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.atmo.arizona.edu%2Fstudents%2Fcourselinks%2Ffall10%2Fatmo336%2Flectures%2Fsec5%2Fholocene.html%5C%22%3E1550%E2%80%931850%20CE%3C%2Fa%3E.%20It%E2%80%99s%20only%20within%20this%20remarkably%20even%20Holocene%20climate%20that%20all%20settled%2C%20agricultural%20societies%20and%20urban%20civilisations%20in%20human%20history%20were%20able%20to%20grow.%20But%20the%20Holocene%20interglacial%20climate%20was%20never%20going%20to%20be%20a%20permanent%20condition%3B%20it%20would%20have%20been%20a%20brief%20warm%20spell%20before%20the%20next%20glaciation%20slowly%20took%20hold.%20Instead%2C%20however%2C%20the%20mass%20combustion%20of%20fossil%20fuels%20over%20the%20past%20250%20years%20created%20an%20accumulation%20of%20greenhouse%20gasses%20causing%20the%20planet%20to%20heat%20up%2C%20thus%20throwing%20that%20longstanding%2C%20ice-age%20climate%20pattern%20out%20of%20whack%3A%20The%20slow%20cooling%20trend%20of%20the%20last%20seven%20thousand%20years%20has%20suddenly%20reversed%20into%20a%20rapid%20warming%20trend.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20984px)%2061vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2045vw%2C%20600px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22193349%2FHolocene-temps_Greenpeace.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22633%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22193349%2FHolocene-temps_Greenpeace.png%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22193349%2FHolocene-temps_Greenpeace-300x180.png%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22193349%2FHolocene-temps_Greenpeace-1024x614.png%201024w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-698408%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22379%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EChart%3A%20NOAA%2C%20using%20data%20from%20S.%20Marcott%2C%20Science%2C%202013%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThere%20hasn%E2%80%99t%20been%20so%20much%20carbon%20dioxide%20in%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20atmosphere%20for%20several%20million%20years%E2%80%94%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Facademic.oup.com%2Foocc%2Farticle%2F3%2F1%2Fkgad008%2F7335889%3Fsearchresult%3D1%26login%3Dfalse%5C%22%3Esince%20long%20before%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20beginning%20of%20the%20Pleistocene%20ice%20age%E2%80%94when%20the%20planet%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fearth.org%2Fdata_visualization%2Fa-brief-history-of-co2%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DThis%25252520was%25252520followed%25252520by%25252520a%2Cdegrees%25252520C%25252520higher%25252520than%25252520today.%5C%22%3Ewas%20a%20great%20deal%20warmer%3C%2Fa%3E%20than%20the%20warmest%20interglacial%20temperatures.%20In%202023%2C%20the%20global%20average%20temperature%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwmo.int%2Fmedia%2Fnews%2Fwmo-confirms-2023-smashes-global-temperature-record%5C%22%3E1.45%C2%BAC%20above%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20average%20of%20pre-Industrial%20times%2C%20far%20exceeded%20the%20Holocene%E2%80%99s%20peak%20warmth%2C%C2%A0%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.downtoearth.org.in%2Fnews%2Fclimate-change%2Fclimate-crisis-has-cost-india-5-million-hectares-of-crop-in-2021-80809%5C%22%3Ethreatening%20agricultural%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fesd.copernicus.org%2Farticles%2F12%2F1503%2F2021%2F%5C%22%3Ereliability%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20other%20civilisational%20infrastructures.%20Our%20present%20planetary%20warming%20trajectory%20has%20overwhelmed%20the%20ice-age%20climate%20cycles%20of%20the%20past%202.5%20million%20years%E2%80%94%3Cem%3Efundamentally%20changing%20the%20very%20planet%20humans%20have%20known%20and%20experienced%2C%20since%20the%20first%20hominins%20learned%20to%20use%20fire%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%E2%80%99re%20propelling%20ourselves%20into%20an%20unknown%20climate%20future.%20Evolved%20to%20thrive%20in%20an%20ice%20age%2C%20our%20bodies%20aren%E2%80%99t%20built%20for%20a%20very%20hot%20world.%20The%20heat%20threshold%20for%20human%20health%20and%20safety%20is%20measured%20as%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fscience%2F2022%2Fjul%2F31%2Fwhy-you-need-to-worry-about-the-wet-bulb-temperature%5C%22%3Ewet-bulb%20temperature%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94a%20measurement%20that%20combines%20heat%20and%20humidity%E2%80%94%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.psu.edu%2Fnews%2Fresearch%2Fstory%2Fhumans-cant-endure-temperatures-and-humidities-high-previously-thought%2F%5C%22%3Eabove%2031%C2%BAC%3C%2Fa%3E%20when%20there%E2%80%99s%20100%25%20humidity.%20Above%20these%20thresholds%2C%20the%20human%20body%20simply%20cannot%20cool%20itself%20fast%20enough.%20Prolonged%20physical%20exertion%20in%20such%20extreme%20heat%20can%20lead%20to%20coma%20or%20death.%20Repeatedly%20labouring%20under%20these%20conditions%20even%20for%20shorter%20spells%20is%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2023%2F06%2F18%2Fworld%2Fasia%2Findia-heat-death.html%5C%22%3Edetrimental%20to%20health%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fkarger.com%2Fanm%2Farticle%2F74%2FSuppl.%2525203%2F38%2F42811%2FClimate-Change-and-the-Kidney%5C%22%3Elinked%20to%20kidney%3C%2Fa%3E%20disease.%20And%20new%20studies%20suggest%20heat-related%20mortality%20may%20be%20even%20more%20closely%20linked%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mdpi.com%2F2073-4433%2F14%2F12%2F1710%5C%22%3Enights%20that%20remain%20very%20warm%3C%2Fa%3E%20rather%20than%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fs43247-023-00897-0%5C%22%3Esimply%20daytime%20temperature%3C%2Fa%3E%20extremes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInstances%20of%20such%20high%20temperatures%20had%20been%20vanishingly%20rare%20in%20the%20human%20past.%20But%20they%E2%80%99re%20becoming%20more%20common%20as%20we%20heat%20the%20planet%20and%20melt%20its%20ancient%20reservoirs%20of%20ice.%20In%20India%2C%20the%20cool%20but%20humid%20monsoon%20weather%20that%20once%20provided%20relief%20from%20summer%E2%80%99s%20heat%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cseindia.org%2Frising-heat-stress-in-india-are-we-prepared--11329%5C%22%3Eisn%E2%80%99t%20cooling%20down%20as%20much%3C%2Fa%3E%20as%20it%20used%20to%2C%20instead%20presenting%20higher%20wet-bulb%20conditions%20and%20already%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC8589686%2F%5C%22%3Enotably%20affecting%3C%2Fa%3E%20health%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencedirect.com%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0160412024000473%5C%22%3Emortality%3C%2Fa%3E.%20What%20will%20happen%20in%20a%20world%20even%20hotter%20by%20one%20or%20two%20degrees%3F%20Humans%20have%20never%20lived%20in%20such%20a%20hot%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%E2%80%99ll%20do%20well%20to%20remember%20that%20we%20are%20the%20children%20of%20the%20Pleistocene%2C%20forged%20by%20the%20power%20of%20fire%2C%20molded%20by%20a%20world%20of%20ice.%20We%20remain%20existentially%20dependent%20upon%20some%20balance%20of%20both.%20But%20those%20of%20us%20acculturated%20to%20industrial%20civilisation%20have%20lost%20all%20awareness%20of%20this.%20In%20our%20insatiable%20and%20reckless%20pursuit%20of%20fire%E2%80%94to%20power%20steam%20engines%2C%20internal%20combustion%20engines%2C%20rockets%2C%20and%20almost%20everything%20else%20we%20use%20to%20build%20out%20the%20human%20world%E2%80%94we%E2%80%99re%20blithely%20sacrificing%20our%20world%20of%20ice.%20Combusting%20mountainous%20quantities%20of%20fossil%20fuels%2C%20far%20beyond%20just%20cooking%20our%20food%2C%20is%20now%20consuming%20the%20planet%20itself%2C%20reshaping%20its%20climate%20and%20ecosystems%20in%20ways%20that%20increasingly%20threaten%20human%20and%20other%20life.%20Having%20forgotten%20our%20once%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fbecoming-human-forged-by-fire%5C%22%3Ecomplex%20relationship%20to%20fire%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20we%20seem%20now%20to%20have%20taken%20on%20a%20new%20and%20blinding%20obsession%20with%20ourselves%E2%80%94a%20dangerous%20hubris%20that%20pervades%20industrial%20age%20cultures%2C%20entailing%20gigantic%20costs%20that%20become%20more%20apparent%20everyday.%20We%20have%20forgotten%20that%20we%20remain%20subject%20to%20the%20same%20laws%20and%20limits%20that%20govern%20all%20living%20systems%20on%20Earth.%20What%20this%20means%20for%20us%20and%20our%20planet%20will%20be%20the%20subject%20of%20next%20week%E2%80%99s%20essay.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EUsha%20Alexander%20trained%20in%20science%20and%20anthropology.%20After%20working%20for%20years%20in%20Silicon%20Valley%2C%20she%20now%20lives%20in%20Gurugram.%20She%E2%80%99s%20written%20two%20novels%3A%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3EThe%20Legend%20of%20Virinara%3Cem%3E%C2%A0and%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3EOnly%20the%20Eyes%20Are%20Mine%3Cem%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1708611091000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F22192550%2FMorteratsch_glacier_1-1.jpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fbecoming-human-shaped-by-ice%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20ice%20age%20shaped%20what%20we%20are.%20And%20in%20it%20we%20thrived.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A2%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fenvironment%2Fbecoming-human-shaped-by-ice%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Engineer%E2%80%99s%20Biofertiliser%20Helps%20Farmers%20Cut%20Costs%20by%2050%25%2C%20Earns%20Him%20Over%20Rs%201%20Crore%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3ETejraj%20Sahu%2C%20a%20farmer%20hailing%20from%20the%20Bargarh%20district%20of%20Odisha%2C%20recalls%20his%20best%20day%20ever%20to%20be%20in%20March%202023.%20It%20was%20the%20day%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noreferrer%20noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thebetterindia.com%2F342788%2Fyellow-dates-farming-in-india-engineer-quits-job-to-become-an-agripreneur%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ethe%20farmer%3C%2Fa%3E%20trusted%20his%20paddy%20field%20with%20a%20new%20fertiliser.%20The%20harsh%20scorching%20sun%20coupled%20with%20unseasonal%20rains%20and%20reduced%20water%20holding%20capacity%20of%20the%20field%20had%20spelt%20trouble%20for%20Sahu%E2%80%99s%20crops%20for%20some%20time.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20just%20when%20things%20were%20looking%20bleak%2C%20he%20got%20to%20know%20about%20a%20new%20fertiliser%20%E2%80%98Navyakosh%E2%80%99%20that%20was%20making%20waves%20in%20the%20farming%20community%20in%20Uttar%20Pradesh.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESahu%20immediately%20got%20in%20touch%20with%20its%20creator%20Akshay%20Shrivastav%20from%20Kushinagar.%20He%20wanted%20to%20understand%20if%20the%20fertiliser%20lived%20up%20to%20what%20it%20promised%20%E2%80%94%20%3Ca%20r